    <item>
      <title>The law on police killings</title>
      <link>http://ramiroau.github.io/etc/wikis/racial_justice/police_impunity/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 02 Jun 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://ramiroau.github.io/etc/wikis/racial_justice/police_impunity/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Una dimensión importante de los casos constantes es que hay &amp;ldquo;impunidad&amp;rdquo;, juega un rol la doctrina de qualified immunity, aparentemente &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qualified_immunity&#34;&gt;totalmente judicial&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Qualified immunity is a legal doctrine in United States federal law that shields government officials from being sued for discretionary actions performed within their official capacity, unless their actions violated &amp;ldquo;clearly established&amp;rdquo; federal law or constitutional rights. Qualified immunity thus protects officials who &amp;ldquo;make reasonable but mistaken judgments about open legal questions&amp;rdquo;, but does not protect &lt;strong&gt;&amp;ldquo;the plainly incompetent or those who knowingly violate the law&amp;rdquo;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
